# Runtime Instantiation And Pooling

- Do not spam `Instantiate`/`Destroy` for frequently created runtime objects; use a pool or factory.
- For Photon Fusion replicated entities, use `Runner.Spawn`, `Runner.Despawn`, scene network objects, or an `INetworkObjectProvider`; do not use raw `Instantiate`/`Destroy`.
- Factory/Application may decide what to spawn; concrete prefab instantiation stays in a Unity boundary, Infrastructure, or Presentation adapter.
- Objects taken from pools must have explicit `Initialize`/`Bind` flow, and explicit `Reset`/`Dispose` flow when returned.
- Network object pooling must clear Fusion-facing subscriptions, predicted visual state, cached authority assumptions, and any per-spawn application binding.
- Pooled objects must not keep stale event subscriptions, tweens, Coroutines, async tasks, or cancellation tokens.
- Pooling optimization must not change gameplay state ownership; do not mix object lifecycle with domain entity lifecycle.
- Even for one-off objects that are not pooled, keep instantiation centralized; do not scatter prefab lifecycle across random views/controllers.
- If disable/pool replaces destroy, test that `OnDisable` side effects do not corrupt gameplay state.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: Deletes and recreates children on every refresh
foreach (Transform child in _content)
{
    Destroy(child.gameObject);
}
Instantiate(_rowPrefab, _content).GetComponent<OrderRowView>().Bind(order);

// GOOD: Row pool has reset/bind flow
var row = _rowPool.Get();
row.Bind(order);
_activeRows.Add(row);
```
